{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your weather app says a 30% chance of rain — do you tote an umbrella or risk getting soaked? Probability thinking is that tiny voice weighing inconvenience against the chance of getting rained on.",
      "title": "Carrying an Umbrella"
    },
    {
      "text": "Traffic apps show several routes with different delay risks. You pick the one that balances time and reliability — like choosing the less crowded checkout line at the supermarket.",
      "title": "Picking a Commute Route"
    },
    {
      "text": "After a medical screening you decide whether to retest or relax. Probability thinking helps turn medical worry into a practical choice about follow-ups and monitoring.",
      "title": "Medical Tests and Decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "At checkout you’re offered an extended warranty. Probability thinking helps you judge whether product failure is likely enough to make that extra cost feel worth it — a small safety net.",
      "title": "Buying Warranties & Returns"
    },
    {
      "text": "When balancing stocks, bonds, or a rainy-day fund, you think in likely ups and downs. Probability helps you spread risk so one bad day doesn’t sink your whole plan.",
      "title": "Managing Personal Investments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Picking fantasy sports lineups or choosing a bet is less gut than estimating who’s most likely to score. You blend past form and matchups into a probability game for bragging rights.",
      "title": "Fantasy Sports and Betting"
    },
    {
      "text": "Shopping for car or home insurance means comparing premiums against accident chances. Probability thinking helps you pick coverage and deductibles that match your comfort with risk.",
      "title": "Comparing Insurance Options"
    },
    {
      "text": "On game shows and quizzes contestants face sure offers vs risky moves. Probability thinking helps decide whether to take the guaranteed prize or gamble for a bigger, less likely win.",
      "title": "Game Shows and Risky Choices"
    },
    {
      "text": "Trying a new recipe for guests? You estimate the chance it will turn out and plan backups (extra time, a simpler dish, or takeout). Probability helps avoid culinary embarrassment.",
      "title": "Recipe Experiments & Dinner Plans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your streaming queue isn’t random — recommendations guess what you’ll watch next. Noticing that lets you spot patterns and avoid getting trapped by autoplay suggestions.",
      "title": "Streaming Recommendations & Autoplay"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine grabbing the last loaves at the supermarket before a big storm: shelves thin, limits on purchases, and suddenly the price stickers feel like a countdown clock. You'll spot how availability and buyer rushes shape what you can buy and when.",
      "title": "Empty Aisles Before a Storm"
    },
    {
      "text": "You refresh the ticket site and hit “sold out,” then watch resale listings climb like an auction. Concerts and sporting events turn scarcity into a scramble—perfect place to notice market pressure on price and access.",
      "title": "Sold-Out Concerts and Resale Frenzy"
    },
    {
      "text": "It’s pouring and your rideshare app shows a 2x multiplier. Click accept and the wait shortens—stand in that car and you’ll feel how short-term demand spikes change what you pay and how quickly drivers respond.",
      "title": "Rideshare Surge on Rainy Nights"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the farmer’s market, summer tomatoes are cheap and abundant; in winter they cost more and disappear fast. Seasonal produce is a simple, everyday way to see availability and price shift with timing and harvests.",
      "title": "Strawberries: Prices by Season"
    },
    {
      "text": "You tour an apartment and three offers arrive by noon—prices leap above the listing as buyers compete. Housing hunts often turn into bidding wars where timing and local demand decide who gets the keys.",
      "title": "Bidding Wars for an Apartment"
    },
    {
      "text": "A sneaker drop goes live, bots check out in seconds, and resale listings pop up at triple the retail price. Streetwear and collectable drops are a flashy example of limited supply meeting huge hype.",
      "title": "Hype Sneakers and Limited Drops"
    },
    {
      "text": "After a holiday, racks full of unsold clothes get slashed 70% to clear space. Clearance events are like the market’s spring cleaning—surplus inventory forces sellers to cut prices fast.",
      "title": "Clearance Racks After the Holidays"
    },
    {
      "text": "Imagine a recruiter juggling three offers for the same software engineer: salaries, signing bonuses, and remote perks climb as firms compete. Job markets make it personal—your skills can change what employers are willing to pay.",
      "title": "High Pay for Hard-to-Find Skills"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Click into a folder that contains subfolders, then subfolders again — the same layout repeats as you drill down. Organizing files turns into a visual trail of repeating structure you recognize instantly.",
      "title": "Nested folders on your computer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull apart a Matryoshka doll: identical shapes hiding smaller versions inside. That tactile 'pattern inside pattern' is the everyday image people reach for when they want to point out repeating structure.",
      "title": "Matryoshka dolls at a market"
    },
    {
      "text": "Slice into a Romanesco or stare at fern fronds: each piece curls into smaller copies of the whole. Nature hands you repeating motifs like a living, edible example of the same pattern at different scales.",
      "title": "Fractal shapes in nature"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open a fractal wallpaper or watch an infinity-zoom clip: shapes keep echoing as you zoom deeper. Artists and VJs use this visual recursion to create hypnotic, endlessly detailed images.",
      "title": "Fractal art and zoom visuals"
    },
    {
      "text": "Think of movies that stack realities—dream inside dream. That cinematic nesting gives you a feel for layered structures: each level is a smaller stage that mirrors the one above it.",
      "title": "Dream layers in films (Inception)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scroll a long comment thread or email chain where replies nest under replies. The conversation grows like a branching tree you can follow, each reply sitting inside another's context.",
      "title": "Email chains and comment threads"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plan a weekend project with tasks, subtasks, and subtasks of subtasks. Your checklist becomes a set of repeating boxes — zoom out and the same outline appears at each level of detail.",
      "title": "To-do lists with subtasks"
    },
    {
      "text": "In games and procedural maps you explore, designers reuse rules so terrain and dungeons echo similar patterns at many scales. Playing feels like moving through a world built from the same building blocks.",
      "title": "Procedural worlds in games"
    },
    {
      "text": "Trace a family tree or organization chart and watch the branching repeat across generations or departments. Each node contains smaller family/teams, a pattern you encounter in genealogy and business diagrams.",
      "title": "Family trees and org charts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Engineers see this pattern every day: nested UI components, parsers that analyze nested expressions, or build systems that reapply rules. It’s the go-to mental model for taming complexity.",
      "title": "A pro's view: engineering patterns"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Você vê o preço riscado e o “novo” vira referência instantânea — aquele preço antigo funciona como tempero: mesmo caro, a oferta parece mais saborosa por comparação.",
      "title": "A âncora dos preços nas ofertas"
    },
    {
      "text": "“Só 2 unidades” ou “promoção termina hoje” acelera a compra. É como pegar o último ingresso do show: o medo de perder nos faz decidir rápido, antes de pensar direito.",
      "title": "Compras por escassez e urgência"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ler muitas 5 estrelas vira sinal: parece o restaurante cheio da esquina. Seguimos o público — a prova social transforma opiniões alheias em atalho para decidir.",
      "title": "Avaliações: seguir a multidão"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na entrevista, o aperto de mão e a primeira frase moldam tudo depois — como a primeira estrofe de uma música que faz você gostar (ou não) do resto.",
      "title": "Primeira impressão em entrevistas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Numa briga de casal, um erro vira replay mental e apaga acertos anteriores. É como focar só na mancha da camisa e esquecer que a roupa inteira é boa.",
      "title": "Ficar preso a um erro no namoro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Segurar ações perdedoras porque é doloroso assumir prejuízo é comum — é como não jogar fora algo estragado por ainda lembrar do preço que pagou.",
      "title": "Investir: custa aceitar perdas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Nos feeds, vemos sempre opiniões parecidas — como conversar num vale onde a voz volta igual. A repetição cria segurança e dificulta ver o outro lado.",
      "title": "Bolhas nas redes sociais"
    },
    {
      "text": "Planejar uma mudança ou viagem e achar que vai durar metade do tempo real? Subestimamos atrasos como quem acha que o trânsito é só um rumor.",
      "title": "Subestimar o tempo de viagem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Um médico que fixa na primeira hipótese pode não abrir espaço para dados novos — como um diretor que insiste numa cena já filmada, mesmo com takes melhores.",
      "title": "Diagnóstico preso à primeira ideia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Depois de um bom jogo, o comentarista diz “ele está em alta” e todos passam a ver com outros olhos. O resultado recente pesa demais na avaliação presente.",
      "title": "Comentário esportivo e “quente”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em jogos ou coleções, evitar arriscar um item raro por medo de perder é comum — é como não trocar uma peça antiga por algo que pode dar mais alegria, por receio da perda.",
      "title": "Jogos e medo de perder itens"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Si entras a un hospital por una infección, habrás notado que algunos antibióticos dejan de funcionar con ciertos gérmenes. Verás pacientes que necesitan tratamientos alternos: es un lugar donde la vida microbiana ya mostró cambios reales a nuestro alrededor.",
      "title": "Hospitales y bacterias resistentes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Un agricultor comenta que un insecticida que antes era infalible ahora falla: las plagas vuelven cada temporada. En los campos la evidencia aparece como problemas de cosecha que cambian con los años.",
      "title": "Campos agrícolas y plagas"
    },
    {
      "text": "En la ciudad, palomas, ratas y zorros urbanos actúan distinto que sus parientes rurales: comen sobras, salen de noche o evitan a la gente. Pasear por un parque te muestra cómo la vida se ajusta a la jungla de asfalto.",
      "title": "Parques y fauna urbana"
    },
    {
      "text": "En la costa los pescadores notan un cambio: cada vez capturan peces más pequeños. Cuando la pesca apunta siempre a los grandes, la comunidad de peces responde con un patrón distinto a lo largo del tiempo.",
      "title": "Pesca y tallas de peces"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si viajas a zonas altas (Andes, Himalaya), verás poblaciones humanas con características que facilitan vivir con menos oxígeno. Es un ejemplo de cómo el ambiente deja huellas visibles en la gente que vive allí por generaciones.",
      "title": "Montañas y vida en altitud"
    },
    {
      "text": "En tu jardín muchas veces el herbicida deja de controlar ciertas malezas: vuelven cada temporada y el producto parece ‘no hacer efecto’. Para el jardinero es un recordatorio cotidiano de cambios en la comunidad vegetal.",
      "title": "Jardín y malezas que persisten"
    },
    {
      "text": "Como aficionado a las aves, puedes notar diferencias de pico entre islas o hábitats: unos comen semillas grandes, otros insectos. Observar los comederos o transectos revela adaptaciones a alimentos concretos.",
      "title": "Avistamiento de aves y comederos"
    },
    {
      "text": "En clases o laboratorios verás experimentos donde bacterias o peces cambian en pocas generaciones. Para investigadores es un taller práctico: la evolución se vuelve algo que pueden seguir en tiempo real.",
      "title": "Laboratorios y estudios de campo"
    }
  ]
}

