{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your paycheck contributions to a 401(k) are like dropping seeds in a garden each month. Over decades those tiny deposits can grow into a big nest egg—start early and the garden gets noticeably larger.",
      "title": "Your retirement account"
    },
    {
      "text": "That minimum payment on a credit card feels small now, but unpaid balances can balloon over time. It’s the reason a small leftover charge can turn into a nasty, months‑later surprise.",
      "title": "The credit card surprise"
    },
    {
      "text": "When a stock pays dividends and you buy more shares with them, your future payouts come from a bigger pile. Think of it as planting fruit trees that later produce even more saplings.",
      "title": "Reinvested dividends"
    },
    {
      "text": "A half‑percent difference in mortgage rate can change your lifetime cost by thousands. On long loans, small rate choices translate into big dollar differences down the road.",
      "title": "Mortgage rate decisions"
    },
    {
      "text": "A viral post multiplies reach: each reshare exposes new people who may reshare again. That chain reaction feels like ripples turning into waves—a familiar compound effect online.",
      "title": "Viral social media growth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Practice guitar 15 minutes daily, and those tiny sessions stack. Skills often build like layers in a lasagna—thin now, but hearty after many layers over months and years.",
